Why America cannot re-elect President Bush
I have never been particularly politically engaged, but these are not normal times.
President George W. Bush threatens the security of the United States and the world and simultaneously undermines American values.
Due to my opposition to him, I was demonized by Bush's campaign team.
President Bush ran for office in 2000 with a platform promising an "humility" foreign policy.
If he is re-elected, this will be a vote for the Bush doctrine of preventive war - and the invasion of Iraq - and the world will have to live with the consequences.
By rejecting Bush's policies at the ballot box, America has a chance to regain the respect and support of the world.
The 9/11 attacks required a strong response.
They also led to the silencing of the critical democratic process - the comprehensive and honest discussion of upcoming issues - which is so essential for democracy.
Bush silenced criticism by labeling it unpatriotic.
For the duration of 18 months following September 11, he managed to suppress all dissent.
In this way, he led America in the wrong direction.
Actually, Bush played directly into Osama bin Laden's hands.
The invasion of Afghanistan – where bin Laden lived and Al-Qaeda maintained their training camps – was justified.
The invasion of Iraq was not.
He was Bush's unintentional gift to bin Laden.
Immediately following September 11, spontaneous expressions of sympathy for America were widespread all over the world.
These have given way to widespread resentment.
More people today are willing to risk their lives to kill Americans than on September 11.
Bush likes to claim that terrorists hate Americans for who they are - a freedom-loving people - and not for what they do.
However, war and occupation bring about innocent victims.
We Americans count our fallen soldiers - more than 1,000 in Iraq.
The rest of the world counts the Iraqis killed every day - perhaps twenty times as many.
Similarly, the torture of detainees at Abu Ghraib prison was not the work of a few "bad apples".
It was part of a system for handling prisoners that was set up by Defense Secretary Donald Rumsfeld.
The world public opinion condemns America, and our troops in Iraq are paying the price for it.
Bush convinced people that America's security was in good hands under him by addressing the fears aroused by the attacks on September 11.
In times of danger, people rally around their flag, and Bush exploited this by fostering a sense of threat.
His campaign assumes that people ultimately don't care about the truth and will almost believe anything if it is repeated often enough.
Something must be wrong with America if we fall for it.
For example, still about 40% of all Americans believe that Saddam Hussein had something to do with September 11, even though the 9/11 Commission - appointed by Bush and chaired by a Republican - clearly established that no such connection existed.
One would like to shout: "Wake up, America.
Don't you realize that we are being led around by the nose?"
The war in Iraq was based on false premises from start to finish - if it ever ends.
It was a war out of choice, not necessity.
More than that, America went to war under a pretext: no mass destruction weapons could be found, and the link to Al-Qaeda could not be proven.
Bush then claimed that America had entered the war to liberate Iraq.
But you cannot impose democracy by force.
Saddam Hussein was a tyrant, and the Iraqis – and the world – can be glad that he is gone.
But America had the duty to ensure justice and order; instead, we watched idly as Baghdad and other cities were looted.
If it really had been about the Iraqi people, we would have had to provide a larger number of troops for occupation.
We should not only have protected the Ministry of Oil, but also other ministries, museums, and hospitals.
Worse still: Where American soldiers encountered resistance, they employed methods – such as entering private homes and mistreating prisoners – that shocked and humiliated the population, fostering resentment and anger.
The retreats and mistakes of the Bush administration are legion.
First, the Iraqi army was dissolved, then America tried to rebuild it.
First, the US tried to eliminate the Baathists, then America sought their help.
When the uprisings could no longer be controlled, America installed an Iraqi government.
The man chosen as their leader was a CIA protégé with the reputation of a "strong man" – a decidedly undemocratic decision.
Despite the efforts of Bush's campaign team to paint a rosy picture, the situation in Iraq is grim.
A large part of the western region was left in the hands of insurgents. The prospects for the conduct of free and fair elections in January are rapidly fading.
Civil war looms.
Bush's war in Iraq has also inflicted immense damage on America, weakening its military power and undermining troop morale.
Before the war, America could project an image of overwhelming strength.
No longer.
Control is slipping in Afghanistan.
North Korea, Iran, Pakistan, and other countries are pursuing new nuclear programs with renewed energy.
One can criticize the Bush Administration on many other political issues, but none of them is as significant as Iraq.
The costs of the war have already reached nearly 200 billion dollars and will continue to rise, because the invasion of Iraq was much easier than the withdrawal will be.
Bush jested with John Kerry that he should explain what he would do differently.
Kerry responded that he would have done everything differently and that he would be in a better position to free us from our entanglement.
But this will not come easily to him either, for America is mired in a quagmire.
Leading military experts and diplomats pleaded with Bush not to invade Iraq.
He ignored them.
He suppressed the critical process with the argument that any criticism of the commander-in-chief would endanger U.S. troops.
But this is Bush's war, and he should be held accountable for it.
The Americans should pause for a moment and ask themselves: To whom do we owe this mess?
A moment of reflection might raise another question: Is Bush's cowboy behavior qualified to keep him as America's supreme commander?
